description.plain:
Born Fatimah Warner, Noname is an American rapper from the historic district Bronzeville in Chicago.

In an interview with The Fader she explained the reasoning behind her name:

I try to exist without binding myself to labels. I’m not really into labels at all, even the way I dress; I usually don’t wear anything with a name brand. For me, not having a name expands my creativity. I’m able to do anything. Noname could potentially be a nurse, Noname could be a screenwriter. I’m not limited to any one category of art or other existence, on a more existential level.

She first saw success as a slam poet, placing 3rd in 2010 in the Louder Than a Bomb competition.

She caught wider attention with a guest verse on Chance the Rapper’s “Lost” from his breakout mixtape Acid Rap. She has also made a handful of features with fellow Chicagoans, on Mick Jenkin’s “Comfortable”, Donnie Trumpet and the Social Experiment’s “Warm Enough” and again with Chance the Rapper on “Israel (Sparring) and “Finish Line/Drown.”

On July 31, 2016, Noname released her debut mixtape, Telefone, which was first announced as early as 2013 and was delayed numerous times.

On September 14, 2018, she released her debut studio album Room 25.

In May 2019, she announced her next project, Factory Baby, on Twitter.

songs.full_title: Shadow Man by Noname (Ft. Phoelix, Saba & Smino)
songs.title: Shadow Man

description.plain:
This song is about death and mortality. Everyone on this song is young, black and talking about their funerals. This is because it’s commonplace in America for black people to be thinking about their mortality at such a young age. So many black lives are taken so soon and it has been this way for generations. This song explores that indirectly without explicitly stating what it’s actually about.

The nightingale symbolizes those departed souls. Those who have lost their lives too soon to violence of all kinds as a result of systematic oppression, from the days of slavery all the way up to the present. This song is wishing them a peaceful rest. It literally reads like a prayer for those fallen ancestors; hence the church/gospel influence in the beat. It’s funeral music.

The Shadow Man is the black man/woman in America. “Please keep your hands up” means to keep fighting, but it’s also an allusion to the “hands up, don’t shoot” mantra that protesters chanted in the aftermath of the Mike Brown shooting.

Shadow Man also features Ralph Gene on drums as well as additional lyrics and vocals by theMIND  & Cam O'bi.

songs.full_title: Diddy Bop by Noname (Ft. Cam O'bi & Raury)
songs.title: Diddy Bop

description.plain:
The Diddy Bop if you’re not familiar is an iconic dance move originated by the man, the myth, the legend, P. Diddy in the 90s. Now it is important to remember that the Diddy Bop like any great dance, isn’t to be boxed in, as it comes in variations. Feast your eyes on one of the most popular forms of the dance.



Because the dance was created back in the 90s this obviously causes Noname’s memories of childhood, and growing up in the Chi to resurface. Back when FUBU, KSWISS,  were way more popular. This song is about childhood and the mistakes that were made but all the joyous times as well.

songs.title: Song 33

description.plain:
“Song 33” is Noname’s first release of 2020. It is a response to J. Cole’s single, “Snow on tha Bluff,” which was released less than two days prior and is largely about Noname’s role in the 2020 movement denouncing racial injustices in the United States.

On the song, she raps about the current state of the U.S. and how black women are disproportionately targeted by many scourges of society, especially the black men that are supposed to protect them.

Noname also calls out Cole for writing and releasing a song responding to a tweet she made rather than making one that discussed more pertinent topics, particularly the extreme mistreatment of black men and women in the United States.

This is her third single to use the “Song & Number” format, following her January 2019 track, “Song 31,” and her April 2019 track, “Song 32.”

songs.title: Yesterday

description.plain:
The first track from Noname’s debut mixtape Telefone, which was first announced nearly three years before the release of this track.

“Yesterday” is about the death of Noname’s grandmother and how that has made her realize that fame and fortune is not all that’s important in life.

songs.full_title: All I Need by Noname (Ft. Xavier Omär)
songs.title: All I Need

description.plain:
Noname balances the pitfalls and potential joy of dating, while acknowledging how difficult creating a project is.

On the 4th track from her debut project she remarks on wanting to create something special for family and friends:

This for my homies; my Umi say love…

At the same time, she wants “a nigga to follow her to the rabbit hole,” an image of falling into a mutual love together.

songs.title: Bye Bye Baby

description.plain:
The 9th track from Noname’s debut project tells a story of an abortion. She masks a traditional birth control remedy (see number 3) with feeding a child with care.

As the song progresses the mother inches closer to explicitly saying what happened “some give presents before they’re even ready” but steers shy of it. She eventually talks to her long gone child; “I’m gonna fall in love again”.
She expresses attempting to move forward from the emotional strife an abortion can cause and realising that the best thing to do is seek happiness “On a lonely road, where happiness needs us”.

We hope she does.

songs.title: Forever

description.plain:
The 8th song on Telefone focuses on self-belief.  More specifically, to believe in yourself despite the inevitable opposition and using positivism to propel yourself forward.  It contains wishful imagery from Noname to make poverty “disappear”.  The first verse in particular focuses on this concept of believing in yourself regardless of any outside negativity.

Noname envisions a world where pure positivity and thought can defeat poverty and grants her home to all with the Spanish phrase, “mi casa es su casa,” meaning “my home is your home.”

The song features chi-town singer Ravyn Lenae who recently released a project of her own as well as Joseph Chilliams who is a member of the Saba including PIVOTGang.

songs.title: Casket Pretty

description.plain:
The seventh track off Noname’s Telefone, “Casket Pretty” is a dark song about death in Chicago.

Noname speaks on police brutality in the wake of what she calls a “brutal” summer. She paints a picture of death, underpinned by  injustice, fear, and a lack of protection and consideration by those who are meant to serve and protect.

songs.title: Blaxploitation

description.plain: Released on September 14, 2018 , this song gets its title from the film genre from the 70s of the same name.  This track features a funky rhythmic bass line that sounds straight off of an old Blaxploitation film soundtrack. It even samples a clip of audio from two of them: Dolemite, and The Spook Who Sat By the Door. Blaxploitation is a fitting title, it being a portmanteau of “Black” and “Exploitation.” The song explores Black stereotypes and the anxieties they cause.

songs.title: Freedom Interlude

description.plain:
http://twitter.com/noname/status/710922572766941184

Weeks after changing her rap name, Noname dropped another single from her mixtape, Telefone. “Freedom Interlude” is a song unbridled by categorisation, as Noname explores a number of different subjects whilst disregarding thematic cohesion.

The song does, however, follow a loose narrative about a woman who exiles herself and, in her loneliness, reaches out to a lover, hoping they will rescue her from that feeling; but no one comes.

She also samples a Nina Simone interview, which acts as the song’s outro.

songs.title: Window

description.plain:
This song is the 4th track off of Noname’s highly anticipated debut album, Room 25. It tells of the short yet intense relationship Noname had with a lover, and the event of her losing her virginity at the age of 25. She talks about how she felt in the relationship, how much she grew as a person, and the magnitude that sex had on the relationship. The battle between love and lust is prevalent throughout her words, and in the hook she is deciding to stop reliving the past and go out into the world to continue growing and succeeding in her craft.

The song is 87 bpm, and contains a dramatic string arrangement on top of African drum patterns with no formal backbeat, giving the song a unique groove that gives the song a feeling of reminiscence and regret with a hint of hope. Paired with Phoelix’s vocal harmonies, the strings have a film score quality to them, which helps add to the element of storytelling that Noname brings to the track.

She talks about how she felt in the relationship, how much she grew as a person, and the magnitude that sex had on the relationship. The battle between love and lust is prevalent throughout her words, and in the hook she is deciding to stop reliving the past and go out into the world to continue growing and succeeding in her craft.

The song is 87 bpm, and contains a dramatic string arrangement on top of African drum patterns with no formal backbeat, giving the song a unique groove that gives the song a feeling of reminiscence and regret with a hint of hope. Paired with Phoelix’s vocal harmonies, the strings have a film score quality to them, which helps add to the element of storytelling that Noname brings to the track.

songs.title: Sunday Morning

description.plain: The hook has a hypnotic vibe and conjures a specific, peaceful image. I feel it has dual meaning – first, it serves as a reminder to always come back to/embrace the here and now of each moment while surrounded by/discouraged by chaos and messed up situations of everyday life; secondly, though, I feel like it serves as a caution – the abrupt ending with the hook cutting the end of the song right off (specifically after the line “don’t get trapped”) is like saying, folks getting too caught up in our own here and now/inner sanctum, that’s what perpetuates these messed up societal situations.
